  "prompt": "What are some words that are the opposite of include?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are some words that are antonyms of \"include,\" along with brief explanations:\n\n1. **Exclude**\n   - **Definition:** To deliberately leave someone or something out.\n   - **Example:** The event will exclude non-members.\n\n2. **Omit**\n   - **Definition:** To leave out or fail to include something.\n   - **Example:** She decided to omit the last chapter from the summary.\n\n3. **Leave Out**\n   - **Definition:** To not include something or someone.\n   - **Example:** Don\u2019t leave out any details in your report.\n\n4. **Remove**\n   - **Definition:** To take something away from a place or position.\n   - **Example:** They decided to remove the outdated equipment from the office.\n\n5. **Except**\n   - **Definition:** Not including; other than.\n   - **Example:** Everyone except John was invited to the party.\n\n6. **Preclude**\n   - **Definition:** To prevent something from happening; to make impossible.\n   - **Example:** High costs preclude the project from moving forward.\n\n7. **Ban**\n   - **Definition:** To officially or legally prohibit something.\n   - **Example:** The school decided to ban the use of smartphones during classes.\n\n8. **Reject**\n   - **Definition:** To refuse to accept, believe in, or agree with something.\n   - **Example:** She rejected the proposal due to its high risks.\n\n9. **Dismiss**\n   - **Definition:** To decide that something is not important or valid.\n   - **Example:** The committee dismissed the idea as impractical.\n\n10. **Cut Out**\n    - **Definition:** To remove or eliminate something.\n    - **Example:** They had to cut out unnecessary expenses to save money.\n\n**Usage in Context:**\n- *To include*: \"Please include all relevant data in your report.\"\n- *To exclude*: \"The package excludes shipping fees.\"\n\nChoosing the right antonym depends on the context in which you're using it. For example, \"omit\" and \"leave out\" are often used when referring to intentionally not adding information, while \"exclude\" can imply a more formal or deliberate action of leaving something or someone out.",
